THIS OVERPACKED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT SPILLED AT THE FEDEX LBBR FACILITY WHERE THE RAMP'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THIS SPILL PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICIES. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THIS PACKAGE WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS.

DAMAGE OCCURRED ON 10/10 AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP GUIDELINES BY AN ANCHORAGE SORT CENTER SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED, BUT DID NOT COME IN UNTIL 10/18. THE MSDS ASSIGNED A 1 DEGREE FARENHEIT FLASH POINT TO THIS MATERIAL, SO I WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND THIS PACKAGE WILL BE HELD PENDING FAA INSPECTION AND RELEASE.

THIS SPILL OCCURRED IN THE MBSA FEDEX STATION WHERE THAT STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED UP THIS SPILL PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP POLICY. THIS PACKAGE CONTAINED TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES THAT HAD THE WARNING OF "KEEP AWAY FROM HEAT AND FLAMES" ON THE OUTER CONTAINER. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND CAME IN LATE ON THE AFTERNOON OF 10/16. THE MSDS ASSIGNED A 105 DEGREE FARENHEIT FLASHPOINT, WHICH WOULD MEAN THAT THIS WAS AN HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS PACKAGE. THIS PACKAGE WILL BE HELD UNTIL THE FAA IS FINISHED WITH THEIR INVESTIGATION AT THE FEDEX MBSA LOCATION.

THIS SPILL HAPPENED IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER WHERE A MEMBER OF THE HUB SPILL CLEANUP TEAM CLEANED  UP THIS SPILL PER FEDEX SPILL CLEANUP GUIDELINES. THE PACKAGE WILL BE HELD IN A SECURE LOCATION UNTIL DISPOSITION INFORMATION HAS BEEN DETERMINED BY THE SHIPPER.

DRIVER HAD LOADED SULFURIC ACID AS INSTRUCTED AND HAD TO ADD A GALLON OF PEROXIDE TO THE LOAD. SAMPLE WAS TAKEN OF LOAD AND THE PRODUCT WAS OFF SPEC. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. AS THE RESULT OF A TWO VEHICLE ACCIDENT, THE CARGO TANK ROLLED OVER RELEASING APPROXIMATELY TWO HUNDRED TWENTY-EIGHT GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. THE CHRISTIAN COUNTY LEPC, TAYLORVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE MORRISONVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. GREYSTONE ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. OF TROY, ILLINOIS RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. GREYSTONE ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. USED VINEGAR TO NEUTRALIZE THE FREE PRODUCT. GREYSTONE ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. REMOVED THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF SOIL FROM THE AFFECTED AREA. THREE (3) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF IMPACTED SOIL WERE TRANSPORTED TO GREYSTONE ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. IN TROY, ILLINOIS FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WHILE TRAVELING ON ROUTE 422 EASTBOUND IN SHELOCTA, PENNSYLVANIA, THE BRIDGE TERMINAL TRANSPORT, IN VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A HEAD ON COLLISION CAUSING THE TRUCK TO OVERTURN ON THE EMBANKMENT.  APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT AND SOIL ON THE ROAD SHOULDER.  SEVERAL CARDBOARD BOXES OF VARIOUS SIZES FELL FROM THE TRAILER AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT.  ONE CARTON CONTAINED ADHESIVES.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF ADHESIVES WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE CARDBOARD  CONTAINER.  THE INDIANA COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  ALL DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO 6 MIL POLY BAGS AND PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER TO BE SENT ON TO THEIR DESTINATION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY CLOSE THE MANWAY. THE MANWAY WAS NOT CHECKED AT HIS CHECKPOINT AFTER LOADING. THIS ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SEEP INTO THE CROWSNEST AND DOWN THE DRAIN TUBES ONTO THE HWY. IN A NARROW STRIP FOR 6 MILES ANOTHER DRIVER NOTIFIED SECURITY AND THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED FOR THE CLEANUP THE DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED WITH OUT PAY UNTIL THE INVESTIGATION WAS COMPLETED AND HAD ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR 5 DAYS AT A LOW PAY RATE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRUCK OVERTURNED INTO THE MEDIAN DUE TO HIGH WINDS WHICH RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. INSTRUCTIONS HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UNIT WAS NOTICED LEAKING PRIOR TO LOADING ON TRAIN. CALLED HAZMAT TEAM TO INVESTIGATE. THEY FOUND 4-55 DRUMS THAT HAVE SMALL PUNCTURED HOLES IN BOTTOM. THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED AT INITIAL LOADING. WHEN DRUMS WERE SLIDING ACROSS FLOOR DRUMS HIT STAR BITS THAT CAUSE PUNCTURE WHEN DRUMS WERE SLIDING. ONLY 1 GALLON WAS RELEASED. HAZMAT TEAM CLEANED UP SURROUNDING AREA AND INSIDE CONTAINER. THEY THEN RELOADED. SHIPPER WILL PICK UP AND HAVE DRUMS TRAINSLOADED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM TRAILER. WHEN OPENED DOOR THERE WAS A TERRIBLE ODOR SO CONTACTED AUTHORITIES LOCAL FIRE, POLICE AND HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO ISOLATE THE AREA FOR CLEANUP. ONCE CONTAINED IEC COMPLETED THE CLEANUP & DISPOSAL THERE WERE NO INJURIES.
CUSTOMER WAS USING THEIR EQUIPMENT AND THE RAIL WENT EMPTY AND DUE TO AIR PRESSURE HOSE JERKED AND FELL OUT INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA. CENTRAL WAS NOT INVOLVED.

column168: THIS INCIDENT PROBABLY OCCURRED IN THE LOADING OF THESE TWO SKIDS. PROPER DUNNAGE WAS USED. AND THE LOAD LOOKED TO BE OK BUT WHEN THESE TWO SKIDS WERE LOADED NEXT TO EACH OTHER, UNDER A LOAD DECK, THE TOP CORNER BOX OF ONE SKID MUST HAVE BUMPED THE OTHER SKID WHILE LOADING NEXT TO EACH OTHER CAUSING THE WRAP AND BOX TO RIP OPEN, THEREFORE CAUSING LID TO POP OFF. LOADER NEEDS TO MAYBE SEPARATE PALLETS W/ SHEET OF PLYWOOD WHEN LOADING NEXT TO EACH OTHER, IN THE FUTURE.

column168: DURING TRANSIT, DRIVER WAS MADE AWARE OF LEAKAGE COMING FROM REAR OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER FOUND SECURE LOCATION ON SIDE OF ROAD AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. WAS CALLED. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED UNTIL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR (FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL) ARRIVED AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM. DUE TO THE EXTREMELY THICK, VISCOUS MATERIAL THE ACTUAL BREACH IN THE DRUM COULD NOT BE LOCATED. THE SPILLED MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS RECOVERED AND THE TRUCK CONTINUED TRANSIT AFTER INSPECTION BY STATE OFFICIALS.

column168: BLOCK 28- FAILURE TO USE DUE CAUTION AND CIRCUMSPECTION. DRIVER #1 RELATED HE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON AMWELL ROAD AND THAT HE WAS SLOWING DOWN BECAUSE A VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM WAS MAKING A LEFT TURN INTO AN UNKNOWN LOCATION. HE ADVISED THAT WHILE HE WAS SLOWING DOWN HIS BRAKES LOCKED AND AS A RESULT HE DROVE OFF THE ROADWAY TO TRY TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM. HE STATED THAT WHEN HE STARTED DRIVING ON THE GRASS HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE AND  IT FLIPPED OVER ONTO ITS SIDE. DRIVER #1 STATED THAT AT THE TIME OF THE COLLISION THE  TRUCK CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 1,800 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, THE ENTIRE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED DID NOT FIT IN THE STORAGE TANK, WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL. FLOW OF PRODUCT WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND CONTAINED. STATE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED. IN ADDITION, A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO ASSIST WITH CLEAN UP. OUT OF CONCERN FOR HAVING REACHED THE RAISIN RIVER, IT WAS CHECKED HOWEVER, NO SHEEN WAS FOUND.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER WHEN HE DISCOVERED LEAKAGE OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE ON FLOOR OF TRAILER. THE PRODUCT IN THE CONTAINER WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER AND ALL SPILLED POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WAS CLEANED UP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR.
column172: Composite, with a rigid plastic inner receptacle for liquids and a steel outer packaging

column168: LEASE DRIVER WAS AT ARIZONA CHEMICAL TO DELIVER PRODUCT. THE OPERATOR WAS CONNECTING TO THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE ON THE TRAILER AND AS HE REMOVED THE CAP, HE WAS SPRAYED WITH A STRANGE SMELLING LIQUID. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LAST PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER WAS STYRENE. STYRENE HAD BEEN LEFT IN THE VAPOR LINE. THE VENT HAD BEEN WASHED IN LAREDO, TX. THE VAPOR LINE WAS NOT CLEANED. OPERATOR FELT DRYNESS IN HIS THROAT BUT WAS OK. ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CONFIRM CLEANLINESS OF A UNIT BEFORE LEAVING A TANK WASH.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: MCKENZIE DRIVER WAS ACCOMPANIED BY INTERNATIONAL PAPER OPERATOR WHILE LOADING TURPENTINE INTO 507-3336. AS THE PRODUCT WAS BEING LOADED, THE MCKENZIE DRIVER NOTICED THE TURPENTINE STORAGE TANK LEAKING. WHEN THE OPERATOR WENT TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAK, THE TRAILER FILLED UP AND OVERFLOWED. THE TRAILER WAS SEALED UP AND THE OPERATOR WASHED THE SPILLED TURPENTINE DOWN A DRAIN. DRIVERS WILL BE ALERT AND AWARE OF UNIT BEING LOADED TO AVOID PRODUCT SPILLS. THIS INCLUDES MONITORING THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER IN RELATION TO THE DISTANCE TO THE DOME LID. THE DRIVER IS NO LONGER EMPLOYED WITH MCKENZIE TANK LINES.

WHILE DANGEROUS GOODS WERE BEING MOVED FROM ONE PALLET ENTERING THE AIRCRAFT TO POSITION 1 LEFT IN ORDER TO MAINTAIN ACCESSIBILITY, A SMALL LEAK WAS NOTED IN 1 OF 10 JERRICANS.  THE LEAKING JERRICAN WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED ON THE ADJACENT MAIN DECK LOADER TO PREVENT FURTHER SEEPAGE ONTO THE AIRCRAFT.  DURING THIS TIME LAPSE, APPROXIMATELY A 6 INCH CIRCLE OF A DANGEROUS LIQUID HAD LEAKED ON THE AIRCRAFT IN FROM OF PALLET POSITION 1L. THE SEEPAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED.  DANGEROUS FOODS CHECKED GOODS PRIOR TO LOADING WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF DAMAGE.

THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION.

UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE CAN WAS PUNCTURED AND THE REMAINING SEVEN CANS WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE CAN WAS DUE TO AN UNKNOWN CAUSE. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, DUSTMASKS, AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND TWO WET CARTONS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE ONE DAMAGED CAN AND SEVEN AFFECTED CANS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING THREE, SIXTY-FOUR OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT ON THE DOCK FLOOR. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED, TWO BOTTLES WERE AFFECTED AND AN ADDITIONAL CARTON IN THE SHIPMENT WAS AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY SIX OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING RUBBER GLOVES, TYVEK SUITS, GOGGLES AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED BOTTLE WITH REMAINING PRODUCT, WET CARTONS AND AFFECTED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE  TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, THREE FIBERBOARD BOXES, IN A SHIPMENT OF 6, CONTAINING 12-1 LITER GLASS RECEPTACLES WERE DAMAGED ON THE DOCK.   UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ELEVEN RECEPTACLES WERE RUPTURED AND 25 UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ELEVEN LITERS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF THE FIBERBOARD BOXES FALLING FROM THE PALLET DURING HANDLING AND HITTING THE FLOOR.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED ABSORBENTS, A BROOM AND A DUST PAN TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FIBERBOARD BOXES AND RUPTURED GLASS RECEPTACLES WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE 25 UNAFFECTED GLASS RECEPTACLES WERE PLACED INTO A 30 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE 2 FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS UNDAMAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column62: Fire, Temperature, or Heat; Incompatible Product
column168: ON SATURDAY, 10/13/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 1145, DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC. ("DART") LOAD NUMBER 123091 CAUGHT FIRE WHILE BEING TRANSPORTED SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 81 NEAR MILE MARKER 152. THE LOAD WAS PICKED-UP ON FRIDAY 10/12/01 AT THE GENERATOR'S FACILITY IN STAMFORD, CONNECTICUT AND WAS EN-ROUTE TO EL DORADO, ARKANSAS. THE LOAD HAD BEEN CHECKED, INCLUDING A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, DURING A STOP APPROXIMATELY 75 MILES FROM WHERE THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED. UPON DISCOVERY, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY DISCONNECTED THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER AND CONTACTED COUNTY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL AND DART SAFETY PERSONNEL. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROTOCOLS WERE THEN IMPLEMENTED INCLUDING CONTACTING ALL APPROPRIATE REGULATORY AGENCIES. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (1-800-424-8802) ALONG WITH THE PENNSYLVANIA EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER (717-787-5027) WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION. LUZERNE COUNTY OFFICIALS TEMPORARILY CLOSED I-81 SOUTHBOUND. AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE, THE TRAILER CONTAINING THE LOAD WAS DAMAGED SO AS TO BECOME NOT ROADWORTHY. THE LOAD WAS THEREFORE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER IN THE PRESENCE OF VARIOUS EMERGENCY/REGULATORY PERSONNEL. THE CHARRED REMAINS OF THE CONTAINERS DAMAGED IN THE FIRE WERE OVERPACKED. THE CONTENTS OF THE TRANSFERRED LOAD AND THE OVERPACKED CONTAINERS WERE DELIVERED TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY.

A UNSECURED DRUM FELL AND WAS DAMAGED.  PRODUCT IS COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUESTED AN ER TEAM AT THE SITE.  THE PRODUCT HAS HIT A SEWAGE DRAIN.  THE PRODUCT IS A CORROSIVE LIQUID CONTAINING COPPER.  THE PRODUCT IS COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THERE IS A STRIP OF 10X100 FEET OF STAINED CONCRETE.  THE PRODUCT HAS IMPACTED A DRAIN.  THE CREW ARRIVED ON SITE AND BEGAN NEUTRALIZATION.  A VACUUM TANKER WAS USED TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT FROM THE SEWER DRAIN.  A PRESSURE WASHER WAS USED TO CLEAN OFF THE CONCRETE AS THE VACUUM TANKER SUCKED UP THE WATER.  THE NORTHEAST REGIONAL SEWER DISTRICT WAS UNABLE TO DETECT ANY CHANGE IN THE WATER

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED PLASTIC DRUM WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF HE SHIPMENT WAS UNDAMAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

A CUSTOMER SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE WAS AT A CUSTOMER LOCATION SERVICING DRUMS WHEN A ONE-QUARTER GALLON SPILL BEGAN DURING LOADING.  THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY AN IMPROPERLY SEALED BUNG ON THE DRUM SPILLING THE PRODUCT ONTO CONCRETE IN THE LOADING AREA OF THE CUSTOMER LOCATION. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT PADS WHICH WERE CONTAINERIZED.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY SEVEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DRIVE SE, IN HEBRON, OHIO FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

WHEN UNLOADING TRLR AT CUSTOMER, IT WAS NOTICED THAT ONE BARREL WAS LEAKING. PRODUCT WAS ON FLOOR OF TRAILER AND THERE WAS A LINE OF PRODUCT FROM THE NOSE TO THE REAR FROM WHERE THE BARREL WAS MOVED WHEN UNLOADING. BARREL WAS PLACED UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING PTL CALLED EMI TO SEND A CLEANUP CREW TO THE SITE. THE CLEAN UP CREW REMOVAL THE WASTE BARREL FOR DISPOSAL. CHEM CENTRAL DISPOSED OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE DAMAGED BARREL. THE DRIVER WAS THEN RELEASED TO HIS NEXT DISPATCH.

column168: EQUILON DELIVERY VEHICLE WAS LOADED TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON INTERSTATE 5 IN THE CITY OF TUSTIN, CA.  THE VEHICLE EXITED THE FREEWAY AT RED HILL AVENUE. THE VEHICLE STOPPED FOR A RED LIGHT AT THE BOTTOM OF THE RAMP AT RED HILL FOR ABOUT 20 SECONDS AND CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP.  THE VEHICLE ACCELERATED MAKING A LEFT TURN ONTO RED HILL.  THE DRIVER REPORTED A LOUD NOISE AND FELT HIS TRAILER BOUNCE AS IF HE HAD RAN OVER SOMETHING.  A WITNESS BEHIND THE VEHICLE SAW SOMETHING FLY OUT FROM UNDER THE TRAILER.  THE WITNESS SAID THE TRAILER DROPPED DOWN OVER THE REAR WHEELS.  INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE REVEALED THAT THE SINGLE LEAF SPRINGS BROKE ON THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRAILER.  AS A RESULT OF THIS MECHANICAL FAILURE, THE PULL TRAILER, LOADED WITH 4700 GALLONS OF GASOLINE, ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.  THE TRUCK DID NOT ROLL OVER.  GASOLINE LEAKED FROM THE DOME LID AND APPROX. 50 TO 100 GALLONS LEAKED ONTO THE STREET.  THE ORANGE COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT USED SOIL TO BUILD UP DAM AND KEEP ANY PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN.  A SMALL AMOUNT DID REACH THE DRAIN, BUT WAS CONTAINED AT THE INCIDENT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DRILLED THE TRAINER AND PUMPED THE PRODUCT TO AN EVANS PUMP TRUCK.  TWO TOW TRUCKS RIGHTED THE TRAILER WHICH WAS RETURNED TO THE SIGNAL HILL TERMINAL.  THE MECHANICS WILL INSPECT THE TRAILER TODAY FOR THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANED UP THE STORM DRAIN AND ANY FREE PRODUCT ON THE STREET.  NO ONE WAS INJURED AND NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED.

column168: (A/B) DRIVER STATES THAT HE WAS CUT OFF BY ANOTHER AUTOMOBILE. AS A RESULT HE HAD TO  BREAK HARD CAUSING LOAD TO SHIFT. DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM TRAILER WHEN HE STOPPED. TWO DRUMS AT REAR OF TRAILER WERE FOUND TO BE DAMAGED. THESE DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND WENT WITH REST OF LOAD  HEAVIER APPROXIMATELY 60 GALLONS OR MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT OF DRUMS. THIS WAS CLEANED UP BY FERGUSON HARBOUR OF MEMPHIS, TN. IT APPEARS THE LOAD MAY NOT HAVE BEEN PROPERTY BRACED.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT AIR PRODUCTS PASADENA, TX PLANT AT 10:30 ON OCT 20TH. LOAD WAS LOADED. WENT TO SCALE, WAS RELEASED AT 12:30. DRIVER WENT AROUND TRAILER TO PLACE PLACARD HOLDERS. CHECKED AROUND TANK AND THEN LEFT. AT 14:45 HE GOT A CALL FROM CNC AND WAS TOLD THAT GUARD AT SCALE NOTICED SOME KIND OF A LIQUID SPOTS ON SCALE AND ASKED IF WE GET HOLD OF DRIVER. DRIVER HAD STOPPED TO DO A TIRE CHECK BEFORE HE WENT INTO STORE HE WALKED AROUND TRAILER AND SAW NO LEAKS. DRIVER THEN GOT THE CALL AND WENT OUT TO TANK AND DID SEE SOME DROPS OF PRODUCT COMING OUT OF BELLY OF TANK, GOT A BUCKET AND PLACED UNDER WHERE DROPS OF PRODUCT WERE. HAZMAT ARRIVED AT 19:00 ON THE 20TH. MCKENIZIE SAFETY ALONG WITH TRAILER S073305 AT 23:00 ON THE SCENE. TRAILER WAS COMPLETE BY 00:30 10-21-01. TRAILER S3073305 WAS TAKEN BACK TO PASADENA TERMINAL AND DELIVERED BACK TO AIR PRODUCTS ON 10-21-01 AT 13:00 AND WAS OUT AT 14:45

DRIVER WAS IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS WHEN THE UNLOADING HOSE DEVELOPED A LEAK. THE DRIVER SHUT ALL OF THE TRAILER VALVES TO STOP THE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING. THE DRIVER AND THE PLANT EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE 1 GALLON SPILL AND REPLACED THE HOSE AND FINISHED THE UNLOADING PROCESS WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column168: A DRIVER AT A SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY SERVICING DRUMS WHEN A ONE HALF GALLON SPILL OF PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED ONTO CONCRETE AS A RESULT OF A LOOSELY ATTACHED LID.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT PADS. THE USED PADS WERE CONTAINERIZED INTO METAL DRUMS.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY TEN POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET, IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS

AFTER TRANSFERRING 99.5% OF THE PRODUCT IN THE CARGO TANK INTO THE STORAGE TANK WITH AIR PRESSURE THE CONSIGNEE STORAGE TANK OVER-FLOWED.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED WITH LIME, WATER AND FLUSHED INTO THEIR FILTRATION SYSTEM.

DRIVER STARTED TO LOAD MOLTEN SULFUR AND AFTER A FEW MINUTES THE DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. DRIVER STOPPED THE LOADING PROCESS ND STARTED TO OUT WATER ON THE VALVE TO HARDEN THE MOLTEN SULFUR TO REDUCE THE AMOUNT OF SPILLED PRODUCT. THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AFTER THE MATERIAL HAD SET-UP. THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO A CTL REPAIR FACILITY AND FOUND THAT THE INTERNAL SULFUR VALVE HAD MALFUNCTIONED AND DID NOT CLOSE PROPERLY THIS WAS THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL. THE VALVE WAS REPLACED BY THE SHOP AND NO FURTHER PROBLEMS HAVE OCCURRED.

TRAILER WAS SPOTTED AT CUSTOMER AND IS IN DEDICATED SERVICE TO ONE PRODUCT. DRIVER WAS REMOVING HOSE WHICH HAD RESIDUAL PRODUCT IN IT.  AS THE DRIVER WAS PULLING THE HOSE FROM THE HOSE TUBE, ONE OF THE LOCKING ARMS THAT SECURE THE CAP/PLUG TO THE HOSE BECAME CAUGHT ON SOMETHING AND THE ARM OPENED ALLOWING THE CAP TO COME OFF AND PRODUCT RAN OUT OF THE HOSE INTO THE HOSE TUBE AND TO THE PAVEMENT.  APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  ACTION TO AVOID RECURRENCE IS TO ASSURE THAT HOSES ARE AS EMPTY AS POSSIBLE BEFORE STORAGE IN THE HOSE TUBES AND TO SECURE THE CAPS AND PLUGS WITH THE VELCRO STRAPS DESIGNED FOR THAT PURPOSE.

column168: ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, DUFFY EXON RESPONDED TO A LEAKING TANK CAR ON TRACK 206 AT THE COLTON, CA RECEIVING YARD. MGR EXON FOUND TANK CAR UTLX 76201 WITH PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND DRIPPING ONTO THE GROUND. HE DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THE TANK CAR WAS OVERLOADED. THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED ON THE ONE SPOT REPAIR TRACK UNTIL IT COULD BE REDUCED. THE SHIPPER, PETROLEUM ASPHALT, REDUCED THE LOAD BY ONE TRUCK LOAD, CLEANED THE SPILL SITES, AND PROPERLY SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

VEHICLE #1 THEN RAN OFF THE ROADWAY RIGHT.  VEHICLE #1 THEN RE-ENTERED THE ROADWAY AND CROSSED THE CENTERLINE OF I-64 WB.  VEHICLE #1 THEN JACKKNIFED AND OVERTURNED. THE METER WAS SHUT DOWN UNTIL RE CALIBRATED.

ON OCTOBER 17, 2001, AT APPROXIMATELY 13:44 P.M., TRIAD TRANSPORT WAS LOADING A 25 YD3 ROLLOFF BIN AT TPI PETROLEUM'S ARDMORE REFINERY. TPI PETROLEUM, INC., IS A WHOLLY OWNED SUBSIDIARY OF ULTRAMAR DIAMOND SHAMROCK CORPORATION. DURING NORMAL LOADING PROCEDURE, AN ESTIMATED 350 POUNDS OF MATERIAL  FROM THE BIN SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS F037 SEWER SOLIDS FROM AN OILY WATER SEWER CLEANOUT, WHICH IS A LISTED WASTE. THE BIN WAS BEING LOADED FOR TRANSPORT TO A TSDF. THE BIN WAS OFFLOADED AND NOT TRANSPORTED ON OCTOBER 17, DUE TO THE INCIDENT. A BACKHOE REMOVED THE MATERIAL FROM THE GROUND, ALONG WITH A PORTION OF THE ROAD, AND PLACED IT BACK INTO THE BIN. THE NRC, LEPC, ODEQ, AND LOCAL DEQ WERE NOTIFIED BY PHONE AT 14:00 P.M., ON OCTOBER 17, 2001.

column168: COMPANY DRIVER ARRIVED AT DELIVERY SITE TO DELIVER GASOLINE TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. CONES WERE PLACED AROUND THE UST FILL-BOX AREA TO WARN SERVICE STATION CUSTOMERS AND DIRECT THEM AROUND THE AREA. A VEHICLE ENTERED THE SERVICE STATION TO FUEL AND WAS POSITIONED TOO CLOSE TO THE CONES AND FILL AREA. WHILE REPOSITIONING THE VEHICLE, THE CUSTOMER RAN OVER THE DELIVERY HOSE DOWNSPOUT FITTING, WHICH CRACKED AND STARTED RELEASING GASOLINE. THE COMPANY DRIVER SHUT OFF THE TRAILER TANK INTERNAL VALVES TO MINIMIZE THE AMOUNT SPILLED AND CALLED 911. A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED BY TERMINAL MANAGEMENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED GASOLINE. TERMINAL REVIEWED THE SIZE AND PLACEMENT OF CONES AT THE STATION AND DETERMINED THAT LARGER CONES AND WARNING SIGNS WOULD BE USED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 99.  OUR DRIVER FAILED TO NOTICE THE VEHICLE IN FRONT OF HIM HAD STOPPED FOR ONCOMING TRAFFIC BEFORE TURNING LEFT ONTO TAFT LANE.  OUR VEHICLE STRUCK THE OTHER VEHICLE CAUSING IT TO BE THROWN OFF THE ROAD.  OUR VEHICLE OVERTURNED AND DIESEL FUEL BEGAN TO LEAK. APPROXIMATELY 4000 GALLONS LEAKED AND 3300 GALLONS WERE RECOVERED.  THE SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND REPLACED.  THE COMPANY HAS HIRED SMITH SYSTEM DRIVING TRAINERS AND HAVE CONDUCTED CLASSROOM & ON THE ROAD TRAINING.  THIS DRIVER WAS RELEASED FOR FULL DUTY AND CHOSE TO RETIRE.  WE HAVE ALSO CONTRACTED WITH A "HOW'S MY DRIVING?" SERVICE. column168: THE VEHICLE AND DRIVER WERE TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 421 WHEN THE DRIVER FELL ASLEEP AND LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE RESULTING IN THE VEHICLE TURNING OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE AND SKIDDING DOWN THE HIGHWAY. THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER BEGAN TO SPILL AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO FLEE THE SCENE. FIRST RESPONDERS FROM YADKIN COUNTY ARRIVED AND BEGAN TO CONTROL THE FIRE AS WELL AS PUT OUT BOOMS TO CONTAIN SPILLAGE, WHICH HAD RUN THROUGH A DRAIN PIPE UNDER THE SOUTHBOUND LANE OF THE HIGHWAY AND WAS MOVING TOWARD A STREAM. THE FIRST RESPONDERS CONTAINED THE FIRE RATHER THAN TRY TO EXTINGUISH IT SO MOST OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WOULD BURN AND NOT LEAVE CONTAINMENT. CAROLINA ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST WERE ENGAGED TO CONTROL THE SPILL AND CONDUCT THE CLEANUP, AND THEY ARRIVED AND BEGAN CLEANUP ABOUT THREE HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT. GEOSCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY P.A. WAS ENGAGED TO DIRECT THE CLEANUP. THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED IN ABOUT THREE DAYS. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AND THE ENVIRONMENT WAS RESTORED TO AS NEAR PREVIOUS CONDITION AS POSSIBLE. COPIES OF THE REPORTS FROM CAROLINA ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST AND GEOSCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY, P.A. ARE ENCLOSED. A COPY OF THE INVOICE FROM THE STATE OF NORTH CAROLINA  FOR REPAIR TO THE ROADWAY IS ALSO ENCLOSED. ALL INVOICES HAVE BEEN PAID.

VEHICLE #2 LOST AIR PRESSURE TO ITS BRAKES AFTER IMPACT AND TRAVELED 769 FEET FROM THE AREA OF IMPACT WITH THE TRAILER DRAGGING ON THE PAVEMENT BEFORE COMING TO REST IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF GA#1. VEHICLE #1 CAME TO REST FACING WEST IN THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF GA#1. THE REASON WHY VEHICLE #1 CROSSED THE ROADWAY WAS UNDETERMINED AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED OCTOBER 31, 2001 DURING UNLOADING OF FUEL FROM CARRIER'S TANK TRAILER TO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANKS.  CONSIGNEE HAD COMPLETED UPGRADES TO THE FUEL OIL DELIVERY SYSTEM AT THE FACILITY SINCE AN EARLIER SPILL IN JULY 2001 (SEE PREVIOUS REPORT).  WIRING ERRORS RESULTED IN A SIMILAR MALFUNCTION OCCURRING AND FAILURE OF THE ALARM SYSTEM.  AN ESTIMATED 1,600 GALLONS OF FUEL SIPHONED FROM THE CARGO TANK VIA THE DELIVERY SYSTEM VENT AND SPILLED INTO THE UNDERGROUND PUMP VAULT.  SPILL WAS LARGELY CONTAINED WITHIN THE VAULT EXCEPT FOR A SMALL QUANTITY THAT ESCAPED INTO AN ADJACENT CATCHMENT.  UPON DISCOVERY OF THE SPILL, THE DRIVER SECURED HIS TANK AND CONSIGNEE RECOVERED FUEL FROM THE VAULT AND CATCHMENT.  CONSIGNEE COMPLETED ADDITIONAL UPGRADES TO THE FUEL DELIVERY SYSTEM TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.  CONSIGNEE HAS SINCE CEASED OPERATIONS AT THIS FACILITY.

column168: A KVS TRANSPORTATION INC CARGO TANK PICKED UP A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE (40,120 POUNDS- HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NO.20960676) DESCRIBED AS "HIGH BOILER WASTE" AT HONEYWELL IN EL SEGUNDO CALIFORNIA AND WAS EN ROUTE TO BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL INC.'S, TACOMA WASHINGTON PERMITTED HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY WHEN A BREACH IN THE INTEGRITY OF THE TRANSPORT VESSEL WAS DISCOVERED DURING A ROUTINE CHECK AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS ON SUNDAY OCTOBER 7TH. THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WAS NORTH OF MEDFORD OREGON ON INTERSTATE 5 (MILE POST 40) WHEN THE PROBLEM WAS FIRST IDENTIFIED. THE DRIVERS NOTED A WET SPOT AND WISP OF VAPOR EMANATING FROM A 1-1/2 INCH DIAMETER PIPING COMPLEMENT ON TOP OF THE TANK. THE LEAK WAS ASSOCIATED WITH A PINHOLE ON THE BOTTOM OF A SHORT HORIZONTAL RUN OF PIPING. THE LIQUID WASTE MATERIAL IS TYPICALLY LOADED UNDER A NITROGEN BLANKET TO MINIMIZE REACTIVITY. THE TANK IS PRESSURIZED WITH NITROGEN DURING THE LOADING PROCESS TO TWENTY PSI AND REDUCED TO ABOUT 2 PSI FOR TRANSPORTATION. UPON DISCOVERY OF THE LEAK THE KVS DRIVERS CONTACTED THE OREGON HIGHWAY PATROL AND A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM WAS ACTIVATED. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, NORTHBOUND AND SOUTHBOUND INTERSTATE 5 WAS CLOSED FOR ABOUT 4 1/2 HOURS. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM, THE TEAM PLACED A NEOPRENE PATCH ON THE BREACH ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PIPING AND STOPPED THE ESCAPING VAPOR. THE OFF-GASSING WAS COMPRISED PRIMARILY OF THE NITROGEN PAD IN THE TANK. A TRACE QUANTITY OF LIQUID RESIDUAL WASTE ADHERING  TO THE INTERIOR WALLS OF THE PIPING MAY ALSO HAVE BEEN RELEASED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. THE EXACT VOLUME OF WASTE RELEASED CANNOT BE ESTABLISHED BUT WAS DETERMINED TO BE NEGLIGIBLE. ACCORDING TO OREGON STATE POLICE LT. DAN DURBIN, "NO HAZARDOUS CHEMICALS  ESCAPED."  THE TRUCK WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELOCATED TO AN ISOLATED AREA (I.E., A NEARBY ROCK QUARRY) PENDING EVALUATION OF THE SHIPPING CONTAINER INTEGRITY. THE MORNING OF OCTOBER 8 AUTHORIZATION WAS GRANTED BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES TO ALLOW THE LOAD TO CONTINUE TO ITS DESTINATION IN THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING CONTAINER AFTER A CONTINGENCY PLAN WAS DEVELOPED AND AFTER APPROVAL AND NOTIFICATION OF ALL JURISDICTIONS IN OREGON AND WASHINGTON THROUGH WHICH THE LOAD WOULD BE TRANSPORTED. ON TUESDAY, OCTOBER 9, THE LOAD CONTINUED TO ITS DESTINATION IN TACOMA, WASHINGTON WITHOUT EVENT AND ARRIVED AT THE TACOMA BURLINGTON FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 1430 HOURS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, OCTOBER 23, 2001, CARLOS BRAMBILA (APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE) WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAFFIC ACCIDENT ON STANDING ROCK ROAD AT MESQUITE, APPLE VALLEY, CA RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 196 LITERS OF "OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID". MR. BRAMBILA, DRIVING AN APRIA HEALTHCARE, 1997 ISUZA FRR TRUCK, CA LICENSE 5R72848, WAS WEST BOUND ON STANDING ROCK ROAD APPROACHING THE UNCONTROLLED INTERSECTION WITH MESQUITE. STANDING ROCK ROAD IS A TWO-LANE ASPHALT ROADWAY. MESQUITE IS A TWO-LANE DIRT ROAD. AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION HE NOTICED A WHITE AUTOMOBILE APPROACHING FROM HIS RIGHT, SOUTH BOUND, AT WHAT APPEARED TO BE A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. HE DID NOT THINK THAT THE OTHER VEHICLE WOULD BE ABLE TO STOP AND INITIATED A HEAVY BRAKING MANEUVER. THE WHITE AUTOMOBILE ENTERED THE INTERSECTION JUST BEFORE MR. BRAMBILA SLID INTO IT. MR. BRAMBILA'S TRUCK IMPACTED THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE WHITE AUTOMOBILE. THE IMPACT AND MOMENTUM CAUSED BOTH VEHICLES TO SLIDE WEST OUT OF THE INTERSECTION. BOTH VEHICLES CAME TO REST ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF STANDING ROCK ROAD. THE WHITE VEHICLE WAS IN THE DIRT, OPEN ACREAGE, FACING NORTH WITH THE FRONT OF THE AUTOMOBILE RESTING AGAINST THE DRIVER SIDE, TOP OF THE TRUCK BOX. THE TRUCK HAD SPUN AROUND AND CAME TO REST ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE, FACING EAST, PARTIALLY ONTO THE DIRT SHOULDER. AT SOME POINT BETWEEN THE TIME OF THE IMPACT AND THE VEHICLES COMING TO REST, SOME OF THE CONTENTS OF THE TRUCK CAME LOOSE FROM THEIR SECUREMENT DEVICES. A 4L200 CYLINDER CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 98 LITERS OF "OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID" WAS PARTIALLY PROTRUDING THROUGH A HOLE IN THE TOP OF THE TRUCK ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE. THE CYLINDER HAD BEEN DAMAGED IN AN UNKNOWN MANNER, WHICH RESULTED IN THE PROTECTIVE RING AT THE TOP OF THE CYLINDER AND THE PRESSURE GAUGE, WHICH HAD BEEN ENCLOSED IN THE RING, BEING BROKEN OFF. THE DAMAGE TO THE CYLINDER RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF THE INTEGRITY OF THE VESSEL. AS THE TEMPERATURE IN THE CYLINDER ROSE, THE "OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID" BEGAN CONVERTING TO "OXYGEN, COMPRESSED", CAUSING THE PRESSURE IN THE CYLINDER TO INCREASE. THIS RESULTED IN THE GRADUAL RELEASE OF "OXYGEN, COMPRESSED" INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. INDIVIDUALS, UNIDENTIFIED, ASSISTED MR. BRAMBILA FROM HIS OVER-TURNED VEHICLE. THE SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE (APPLE VALLEY CONTRACT OFFICE) AND THE APPLE VALLEY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO SCENE. THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS IDENTIFIED AS A WHITE 1995 MITSUBISHI ECLIPSE, CA LICENSE 4EFP267. THE DRIVER AND THREE PASSENGERS HAD TO BE EXTRACTED FROM THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER WAS PRONOUNCED DEAD AT THE SCENE. TWO OF THE PASSENGERS WERE TRANSPORTED VIA MEDICAL HELICOPTER TO THE ARROWHEAD REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER AND THE THIRD PASSENGER WAS TRANSPORTED VIA AMBULANCE TO ST. MARY MEDICAL CENTER. THE APPLE VALLEY FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED A ONE-MILE RADIUS DUE TO THE OXYGEN RELEASE. THEY PROCEEDED TO OPEN A LARGE HOLE IN THE TOP OF THE TRUCK TO INSPECT THE CONTENTS. THEY THEN DIRECTED JOSE OTE

AT THAT TIME I SPOKE WITH A GENTLEMAN NAMED TIMOTHY UNDERWOOD AT A CLEAN HARBORS FACILITY IN ALBANY, NEW YORK. MR. UNDERWOOD THEN DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW AT 1935. UPON ARRIVING ON SCENE THE CLEAN HARBORS RESPONSE CREW UPRIGHTED AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM IN QUESTION. THE WASTE STREAM WAS AN ARSENIC WATER SOLUBLE AND APPROXIMATELY 30-35 GALLONS WERE LOST TO DATE, THERE HAVE BEEN NO FIGURES PASSED ALONG TO DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC CONCERNING PRODUCT LOST AND CLEAN-UP COSTS.

column168: CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT A 50 LB. BAG CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLID HAD BEEN TORN. APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED, IMPACTING THE TRAILER FLOOR. CF PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE MATERIAL AND PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM. THE DRUM WAS STORED PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS. CF PERSONNEL REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT INC (E.M.I. JOB #12969). THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE. E.M.I NOTIFIED MR. ANDY GAY (CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER) OF THE INCIDENT.

CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT A TOTE TANK WHICH WAS STACKED ON A DRUM WAS LEAKING. THE LIQUID HAD DRIPPED ON THE DRUM AND A WOODEN PALLET. APPROXIMATELY 12 OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. CF PERSONNEL NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC (E.M.I.).E.M.I. CONTACTED LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO RELEASE (E.M.I. JOB #12955) RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND BEGAN CLEANUP OPERATIONS. RESPONSE TEAM DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A CRACK IN THE BOTTOM LEFT CORNER OF THE TOTE TANK. THE CRACK WAS SEALED WITH EPOXY TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE. THE IMPACTED DRUM WAS WIPED DOWN. THE WOODEN PALLET WAS BROKEN DOWN AND PLACED IN A 55-GALLON DRUM WITH THE CLEANUP MATERIAL. THE TOTE TANK AND THE DRUM OF CLEANUP MATERIAL WERE LEFT ON SITE AS PER CF'S INSTRUCTION. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES IN REGARDS TO THIS INCIDENT.

FREIGHT WAS BEING LOADED TO UCB BY CHRIS OROGCO DSR(UB4). DRUMS WERE ON PALLET, CONTAINING 4. THEY  WEREN'T WRAPPED, BANDED, SECURED. HE WAS ALSO ENTERED INTO SOS, IN THE GIVEN AN LOI, AND RE-CERTIFIED ON A FORKLIFT.

MATT BREWER, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED HE DISCOVERED A LEAKING CONTAINER IN THE POCATELLO RAIL YARD. THE CONTAINER WAS SET OUT IN THE NUMBER FOUR DEPOT UNTIL IT COULD BE INSPECTED. THE CONTAINER APLU 490788 WAS INADVERTENTLY RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION. BRENT PETERSON, SENIOR MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED CONTAINER APLU 490788 HAD BEEN DELIVERED AND SET OUT IN GREEN RIVER, WY. HARRY RODABOUGH, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED. MGR. RODABOUGH CONTRACTED WITH PACIFIC WEST TO RESPOND TO GREEN RIVER, WY. PACIFIC WEST INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND DETERMINED THAT A 250 GALLON TOTE HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY OTHER FRIGHT. PACIFIC  WEST HANDLED REMEDIATION OF THE CONTAINER AND DISPOSAL OF SPILLED PRODUCT. column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON THURSDAY, 10/4/01, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS T.M. ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED BY FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR MR. JAMES DUNCAN. DUNCAN RELATED THAT TANK CAR DODX 14306, LOCATED IN TRACK 202 AT THE LIVONIA YARD WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP. ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN. ROBINSON CLOSED THE VALVE AND THIS STOPPED THE PRODUCT FROM DRIPPING. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED OUT EVAPORATED FROM THE BALLAST AND TIES. ROBINSON CONTACTED THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER WHO IN TURN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC AS WELL AS THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.

ON 10/4/2001, 1000 HOURS MR. PHIL MARQUIS FROM THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION ADVISED SAHM DAVE JACKSON OF A LEAKING TANKCAR AT THE OLD YARD, STOCKTON CA.  MR MARQUIS AS PART OF HIS AUDIT PROGRAM FOUND GATX 61120 LEAKING NEAR THE SAFETY VENT. THE STOCKTON FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS WERE ON THE SCENE. SAHM JACKSON DONNED APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE OUTFIT EQUIPMENT AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR. HE FOUND ALL BOLTS ON THE SAFETY VENT WERE LOOSE AND THE UNLOADING PIPE ADAPTER WAS MISSING TWO BOLTS WITH THE OTHER TWO WERE BARELY THREADED. HE WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE SAFETY VENT BUT NEEDED ADDITIONAL BOLTS TO SECURE THE UNLOADING PIPE. HE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER CHEMICAL TRANSFER, MR NEIL ELLIS. MR ELLIS RESPONDED AND SECURED ALL FITTINGS. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND. MR. MARQUIS ADVISED HE WOULD BE WRITING UP A NOTICE OF VIOLATION PER CFR 49 SECTION 173.31, IMPROPER SECUREMENT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 100501 AT APPROXIMATELY 520 AM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED NOTICE OF A LEAKING TANK CAR FROM THE RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER. RESIDENTS IN KINDER, LOUISIANA NOTICED AN ODOR FROM A PASSING TRAIN AND NOTIFIED THE SHERIFF'S OFFICE. THE SHERIFF NOTIFIED THE RAILROAD AND THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED FOR INSPECTION IN OBERLIN, LA. THE CONDUCTOR WALKED THE TRAIN AND DISCOVERED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM UTLX 201126. A SMALL WET AREA WAS ALSO OBSERVED ON THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER REEDER.  REEDER APPROACHED THE CAR, REMOVED SEAL BT 091354, OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, AND FOUND THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE VALVE STEM OF THE LIQUID VALVE. THE VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED.  REEDER CLOSED THE VALVE THEN TIGHTENED THE PACKING NUT. THE LEAK STOPPED. THE REMAINING LIQUID EVAPORATED. THE TRAIN WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT. NO ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION WAS REQUIRED.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

TOM WATSON, YARD MASTER, ADVISED TANK CAR, PTLX223808, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AND HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN YARD 1 TACK 522. DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED RMCC TO CONTACT CHEMTREC. MR. JOHNSON REQUESTED CONFERENCE CALL WITH SHIPPER CONTACT WHEN AVAILABLE.  DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, ADVISED STEVE ADDISON, EQUVIOUS SERVICES, THAT THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS MISSING A MANWAY GASKET, A BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE, AND TWO MANWAY BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT. REPAIRS TO THE EXCEPTIONS WERE MADE AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 5:45PM RMCC CONTACTED MIKE KELLY, MGR. CTS, AND ADVISED THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED AS LEAKING IN A TRAIN STOPPED AT STONEBURG, TX. MGR KELLY RESPONDED AND HIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE BOLTS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WERE LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. KELLY WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS AND SECURE THE LEAK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM AND THE REPAIRS MADE TO THE TANK CAR.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON 10/16/2001, 0925 HOURS LATHROP INTERMODAL MANAGER GASTINEUA REPORTED A LARGE LEAK FROM A CONTAINER THAT HAD JUST ARRIVED ON THE ZLCBR 15 INTO THE LATHROP CALIFORNIA FACILITY. PER MS. GASTINEAU, THE LOAD WAS A MIXED SHIPMENT OF BOTH FLAMMABLES AND CORROSIVES. SAHM DAVE JACKSON AND SAHM DAVE SACHS RESPONDED AND FOUND A ONE GALLON PER MINUTE LEAK COMING FROM THE REAR OF CONTAINER TPHU 483208. THEY IMMEDIATELY ORDERED ABSORBANT AND DETERMINED THERE WERE NO WATER DRAINS IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA. A PH  PAPER WAS USED AND CAME BACK WITH A READING OF 1 PH. THEY REQUESTED RMCC MAKE ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS. DUE TO THE SEVERITY OF THE LEAK, MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED FOR AN IMMEDIATE RESPONSE.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL MADE NOTIFICATION TO THE CUSTOMER. AT APPROXIMATELY 1040 HOURS, MANAGER CHRIS ACCELLENI, MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AND TOGETHER WITH SAHM JACKSON MADE AN ENTRY AND OBSERVED ONE 275 GALLON TOTE HAD FAILED. THE TOTE WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO THIRDS INTO THE CONTAINER AND HAD FAILED DUE TO THE LOAD BEING IMPROPERLY SECURED WITH TYGUARD AT THE DOOR. THEY ALSO OBSERVED ANOTHER TOTE AT THE DOOR THAT WAS STARTING TO FAIL WITH THE PROTECTIVE METAL CAGE BROKEN AROUND THE PLASTIC STORAGE CONTAINER.  APPROXIMATELY 235 GALLONS OF ZEP CLEANER #7961(PHOSPHORIC ACID) WAS LOST FROM THE FIRST TOTE. THERE WERE A TWO ADDITIONAL TOTES IN THIS CONTAINER THAT WERE DAMAGED. ONE TOTE HAD A DAMAGED CAGE, AND THE OTHER TOTE HAD A DAMAGED CAGE WITH A SLIGHT PUNCTURE AT THE TOP WHICH RELEASED LESS THAN A GALLON OF PRODUCT. MR. MORGAN REPORTS ZEP MANUFACTURING HARRY VERNON ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND PROVIDED INFORMATION FOR A DIRECT BILLING. ALSO MAKING A SITE INSPECTION WAS SAN JOAQUIN COUNTY HEALTH INSPECTOR MICHELLE STEMI-LEE.

column168: PAUL HARRYMAN,MYO, REPORTED FREON LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR DUPX20178 IN THE GARRETT YARD, ARLINGTON,TX ED MCNUTT, MEFO, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED WITH MR. HARRYMAN. MGR MCNUTT BROKE THE SEAL ON DUPZX 20178, SEAL NO. INEOS FLUOR 0003161 AND DISCOVERED THE LIQUID LINE ON THE B-END OF THE CAR WAS PARTIALLY OPEN.  THIS WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG SECURED. ADDITIONALLY, THE VAPOR LINES WERE TIGHTENED AND THE FROZEN ICE FROM THE DOME WAS REMOVED. THE BONNET WAS SEALED WITH SEAL NUMBER UPRR CTS 0006059. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

E.M.I. JOB NUMBER: 13167 A FIBERBOARD CARTON CONTAINING A PLASTIC PAIL OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS DROPPED DURING UNLOADING CAUSING THE CARTON AND THE PAIL TO SPLIT.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF ACID WAS SPILLED ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR.  CF PERSONNEL APPLIED A NEUTRALIZING ABSORBENT AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL BY ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT.

CF PERSONNEL WERE PREPARING TO UNLOAD TRAILER.  WHEN THEY OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS THEY NOTICED A STRONG ODOR.  THE DOORS WERE CLOSED AND THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA.  CF PERSONNEL NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT (JOB #13137).  RMCAT WAS DISPATCHED BY ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WERE SIX CYLINDERS LAYING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR UNSECURED.  THE RESPONSE TEAM INSPECTED THE CYLINDERS AND DISCOVERED THAT THE VALVES ON TWO OF THE CYLINDERS WERE LOOSE.  THE VALVES WERE TIGHTENED AND RECHECKED FOR LEAKS.  NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT NOTIFIED MR. MIKE KILLOUG (CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER) OF THE INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.
column172: Cylindrical metal container, not for compressed gases (i. e., not a pressure vessel)

column168: CF PERSONNEL WERE UNLOADING TRAILER.  AS THEY UNLOAD A FREIGHT ITEM THEY NOTICED A PILE OF POWDER IN FRONT OF ANOTHER PALLET LOADED WITH BAGS.  CF PERSONNEL EXITED THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA AT THE TERMINAL THE BILL OF LADING WAS REVIEWED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PALLET WAS LOADED WITH 50 POUND BAGS OF SULFAMIC ACID.  CF PERSONNEL NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR-ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. , (E.M.I. JOB #13130).  E.M.I. PERSONNEL REVIEWED THE MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT AND DETERMINED THAT AN ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR (FERGUSON HARBOUR INC.) WOULD BE DISPATCHED TO THE TERMINAL TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND MADE ENTRY.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO OF THE 50 POUND BAGS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN PUNCTURED.  THE TWO BAGS WERE LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BAGS HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT WHEN THE PALLET WAS LOADED INTO THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THE TWO DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED IN A 55-GALLON POLY-DRUM AND LABELED.  AS PER CF PERSONNEL'S INSTRUCTION THE DRUM CONTAINING THE DAMAGED BAGS WAS LEFT ON SITE (TO BE DELIVERED TO CUSTOMER). NO OTHER WASTE WAS GENERATED.  E.M.I. CONTACTED THE CF REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER (TIM MURPHY) AND NOTIFIED HIM OF THE INCIDENT.

YOUNG BERG WAS ALSO INSTRUCTED ON HOW TO BLOCK AND BRACE FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF. CONTACTED ICTF SECURITY, WHO STATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS NOTED IN PARKING STALL GREEN #359, AND WAS DRIPPING AN UNKNOWN LIQUID. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND NOTED A SMALL PUDDLE OF PRODUCT, LESS THAT ONE PINT, ON THE PAVEMENT FORWARD OF THE CHASSIS WHEELS. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IF COULD BE ISOLATED AND CONTAINED PENDING AN INSPECTION. DUE TO THE CONFIGURATION OF THE LOAD, WHICH CONSISTED OF 55 GALLON DRUMS, THE EXACT SOURCE OF THE LEAK COULD NOT BE DETERMINED. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT LEAKED, THE CONTAINER WAS SET UP TO CAPTURE ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKING PRODUCT, AND ALLOWED TO SET OVERNIGHT, WHERE THE SHIPPER COULD BE CONTACTED THE FOLLOWING MORNING, ONCE THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE LADING AND INSPECT  THE DRUMS. ONE DRUM WAS LOCATED FOUR ROWS IN FROM THE REAR DOORS, ON THE RIGHT SIDE WALL, THAT HAD A SMALL TEAR IN THE BOTTOM CHIME. THE TEAR WAS CAUSED DURING THE LOADING OF THE CONTAINER, AS THE DRUM CLIPPED AN ELEVATED FLOOR SCREW HEAD, CAUSING THE METAL TO FOLD. DURING TRANSPORTATION, THE HYDRAULIC SURGE OF THE LIQUID IN THE DRUM, CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT THE TEAR IN THE CHIME. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK DRUM FOR RETURN SHIPMENT TO THE POINT OF ORIGIN, PER THE SHIPPER REQUEST. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE INSPECTED AND RELOADED INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER ONCE THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE. RMCC MADE THE NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.
